OWERRI – The Imo State Government has approved a mobile money/agent banking training (FINTECH) programme for 5,000 youths in the state. According to Okechukwu Umez-Eronini, the Commissioner for Youths and Social Development, the programme, which is an initiative of the state Ministry of Technology Development, in partnership with the Iwuanyanwu Foundation and E-Transact International Plc, also in collaboration with the state Ministry of Youth and Social Development, is aimed at making empowerment and skill acquisition available to the youths. Umuezu-Eronini, who disclosed this at the flag-off of the programme in Owerri, said that with it, the youths would develop a positive attitude towards being self-reliant and not dependent on white collar jobs which would help in improving their quality, standard and entrepreneurial skills. According to Eronini, the innovation when fully implemented would create a crop of technologically and financially literate youths, empower them, eliminate high rate of crime and crime-related activities in the state by bringing financial services closer to the people of the state in their various localities and also enhance the GDP of the state. Chief Emmanuel Iwuanyanwu, the founder/ chairman of Iwuanyanwu Foundation, said as an organisation established in 1988 which seeks ways and means of improving the quality and standard of life of the people, the organisation had, since incorporation, played major roles in fighting unemployment in the state. This, he said, it has done through the award of scholarships to gifted students. Iwuanyanwu commended Governor Emeka Ihedioha for according priority to the welfare of youths in the state and enjoined the people of the state to support his administration which he said was divinely installed for the liberation of the masses. Governor Ihedioha, who flagged off the programme through his deputy, Gerald Irona, said his Rebuild Imo Project was anchored on security, human capital development, infrastructure and technological development. The governor added that youth employment, good governance and the welfare of the people would continue to enjoy a pride of place in his administration, adding that partnering with the organized private sector was crucial to move the state forward.